1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:05,617
In Vienna, two maternity wards sat under

2
00:00:05,617 --> 00:00:06,996
one hospital roof.

3
00:00:06,996 --> 00:00:08,376
The First Clinic was

4
00:00:08,376 --> 00:00:09,700
run by doctors and students.

5
00:00:10,602 --> 00:00:12,144
The Second was run by midwives.

6
00:00:12,926 --> 00:00:14,087
The patients were similar.

7
00:00:14,868 --> 00:00:16,111
The death rates were not.

8
00:00:17,071 --> 00:00:20,185
By 1846, the First Clinic was losing

9
00:00:20,185 --> 00:00:22,440
more than one in ten mothers.

10
00:00:22,440 --> 00:00:25,436
Across the same years, the Second stayed

11
00:00:25,436 --> 00:00:26,623
under four percent.

12
00:00:26,623 --> 00:00:27,810
Semmelweis found the

13
00:00:27,810 --> 00:00:28,989
difference in the routine.

14
00:00:29,048 --> 00:00:32,435
Doctors moved from autopsies to childbirth

15
00:00:32,435 --> 00:00:34,193
without effective disinfection.

16
00:00:34,193 --> 00:00:35,950
He

17
00:00:35,950 --> 00:00:37,655
required chloride-of-lime hand

18
00:00:37,655 --> 00:00:39,144
disinfection.

19
00:00:39,144 --> 00:00:40,632
Mortality fell.

20
00:00:40,632 --> 00:00:42,121
The evidence

21
00:00:42,121 --> 00:00:44,206
worked before germ theory could explain

22
00:00:44,206 --> 00:00:45,490
why.

23
00:00:45,490 --> 00:00:46,774
That was the problem.

24
00:00:46,774 --> 00:00:49,020
Believing the data meant believing doctors

25
00:00:49,020 --> 00:00:50,920
had been carrying death from the dead

26
00:00:50,920 --> 00:00:52,082
to the living.

27
00:00:52,082 --> 00:00:53,244
The institution protected

28
00:00:53,244 --> 00:00:55,693
its identity longer than it protected the

29
00:00:55,693 --> 00:00:57,380
evidence.

30
00:00:57,380 --> 00:00:59,066
Small causes, massive

31
00:00:59,066 --> 00:01:00,392
consequences.
